					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8601274#post-4181717</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8601274/scp-4416#post-4181717</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 12 Mar 2019 06:19:24 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Lt Flops</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1735419</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>The &quot;non-anomalous&quot; aspect is only brought up once in any formal manner.</p> <p>The description <em>does</em> mention that they're investigating whether SCP-4416 has an anomalous property they aren't aware of. As well, researcher debate and an agent's further exploration both attempt to discern a potential anomaly. And then at the very end, the article finally explains why this didn't seem anomalous before: the anomaly is an antimemetic Sensory Extrapolation (SEP)<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-410856-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" >1</a></sup> field that surrounds a devious shark entity, and punching sharks in its vicinity strengthens its memetic irrelevance.</p> <p>I think it's an interesting concept that not <em>everything</em> is explicitly anomalous, every single time. This sort of idea gives more realism to the SCP canon&#8230; Well, except for the Shark Punching Center aspect. And you also have to consider: all information about each anomaly, up to and including the formal &quot;reveal&quot;, must be documented <em>somewhere</em> in Foundation storage. It's our framing of this information as readers and writers, respectively, that's being manipulated here, and (IMO) with good reason.</p> <p>But that's just my two cents (as the person that wrote the darn thing 😉).</p> <div class="footnotes-footer"> <div class="title">Footnotes</div> <div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-410856-1"><a href="javascript:;" >1</a>. Yes, the one from Hitchhiker's guide, also mentioned as a legitimate concept in SCPs-2721 and -4774.</div> </div> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8601274#post-4181407</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8601274/scp-4416#post-4181407</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Mon, 11 Mar 2019 23:30:52 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>MarqFJA87</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1895233</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>&#8230; How can this be an SCP if it's explicitly described as &quot;non-anomalous&quot;? And then there's the Level 4 collapsible contradicting all the insistence that the phenomenon is non-anomalous by explicitly proposing reclassification as a &quot;Thaumiel-class <strong>anomaly</strong>&quot;.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
